==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manoeuvre
<hw>Ma*noeu"vre</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>manoeuvre</ets>, OF. <ets>manuevre</ets>,
LL. <ets>manopera</ets>, lit., hand work, manual labor; L.
<ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>opera</ets>, fr. <ets>opus</ets> work. See
<er>Manual</er>, <er>Operate</er>, and cf. <er>Mainor</er>,
<er>Manure</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Management; dexterous movement; specif., a military
or naval evolution, movement, or change of position.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Management with address or artful design; adroit
proceeding; stratagem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoeuvre</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Maneuver</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Manoeuvre
<hw>Ma*noeu"vre</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v.
i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maneuvered</conjf>
<pr>(#)</pr> or <conjf>Manoeuvred</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Maneuvering</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, or <conjf>Manoeuvring</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manoeuvrer</ets>. See
<er>Maneuver</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To perform a
movement or movements in military or naval tactics; to make changes in
position with the intention of getting an advantage in attack or
defense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To make changes in one's
approach to solving a problem, so as to achieve maximum advantage in a
changing situation; -- used especially in competitive situations, as in
politics, diplomacy, or sports.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To manage with address or art; to scheme.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoeuvre</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Maneuver</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

